(a small fire had started in dead underbrush, sparked by a careless hiker’s cigarette
but because the children had worked so hard
the healthy trees resisted
the flames found no easy path
rangers arrived quickly and contained it before it could spread)

danger, the feeling said.
fire.

from that season forward, whenever the wind moved through the redwoods
people in the village said they could almost hear the trees singing

in the shadow of an ancient redwood forest lived a girl named mira who could hear trees speak
not in words, exactly
but in slow, deep feelings that came through her bare feet when she walked the mossy paths

later, mira sat again with grandfather cedar
the feeling now was different: gratitude, warm and slow like sunlight through leaves

mira returned to grandfather cedar
the feeling grew stronger, sharper
she sat beneath him for three days, listening
on the fourth day she understood: not wildfire from outside
but rot from within
a sickness spreading through roots
carried by beetles too small to see

she gathered the village children
together they collected sap from healthy trees
mixed it with herbs the elders knew
and painted the mixture on the trunks nearest grandfather cedar
it was a desperate, hopeful gesture

she leaned against him and whispered
we heard you

she ran to the ranger station
the forest is afraid, she told them
there's going to be a fire

(the whisper of the redwoods)

the forest answered in the rustle of a thousand branches
a sound like breathing
like thanks

the oldest tree, grandfather cedar
was over a thousand years old
his voice was the slowest of all
a low vibration that took days to form a single thought
one spring, mira pressed her palm to his rough bark and felt something urgent

the rangers smiled kindly but explained there had been no lightning
no campfires left burning
the season is wet, they said
everything is safe

weeks passed
summer came hot and dry
one morning mira woke to smoke—not thick
not raging
but thin and acrid
she ran to the forest